The best approach for file system statics is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already wraps `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, and more.

### 1. Install the package

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

For your test project:
```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Inject `IFileSystem` instead of using statics

Refactor `ReportGenerator` to accept `IFileSystem` via constructor injection:

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

namespace NeedsWrappers.Services;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
        {
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);
        }

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}.txt");
        var content = $"Report: {reportName}\nGenerated: {DateTime.UtcNow:O}";

        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, content);
        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

The mapping is straightforward — every static you mentioned has a direct equivalent:

| Static call | Replacement |
|---|---|
| `File.ReadAllText(...)` | `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(...)` |
| `File.WriteAllText(...)` | `fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(...)` |
| `Directory.Exists(...)` | `fileSystem.Directory.Exists(...)` |

### 3. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs:
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers;

var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
Assert.Contains("Report: sales", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
```

`MockFileSystem` gives you a fully in-memory file system — no temp files, no cleanup, and tests run in parallel safely.

> **Bonus:** Your `ReportGenerator` also uses `DateTime.UtcNow` and `Environment.*`. Since you're on .NET 10, you can inject the built-in `TimeProvider` for time, and a small custom `IEnvironmentProvider` for the environment calls, using the same pattern. Want me to generate those too?
